Yes — **line 288 is exactly the correct place.**

You are currently at the **end of the stylesheet**, right after this block:

```
.directory-content p {
    max-width: 520px;
    margin: 12px 0;
}
```

So immediately **below line 287**, you add:

```css
.site-frame {
  max-width: 1200px;
  width: 92%;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

So the bottom of your file will look like this:

```
.directory-content p {
    max-width: 520px;
    margin: 12px 0;
}

.site-frame {
  max-width: 1200px;
  width: 92%;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

Then simply:

**1. Save**
```
Ctrl + S
```

**2. Commit**
Use the Source Control panel in VS Code.

Suggested commit message:

```
add global site-frame width constraint
```

**3. Push**

After that we will do the **second half** of the fix — adding the wrapper to the chamber HTML pages — which will take about **30 seconds per page**.

And just to confirm your instinct earlier:  
your idea of placing the **search box beneath the cabinet between the lower plinths** is architecturally very sound. That space is exactly the kind of **intentional negative space** classical builders used for inscriptions, seals, or mechanisms.
